\begin_layout Subsubsection
Security
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the system can be accessed through networks, a password will be required
 to permit the access to the internal web server.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Access to user's manual will be unprotected.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Clock precision
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As mentioned in section 
\series bold
2.4.
 constraints 
\series default
the project will be based on the ARDUINO platform and this affects an important
 parameter: the clock accuracy that deserves comment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although the Atmel 328P
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Used in ARDUINO UNO/Yún
\end_layout

\end_inset

 MCU clock leaves the factory with a standard calibration, its accuracy
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The accuracy of the factory calibration is within +/-3 or +/-10% .
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is not enough in the long term for a reliable clock.
 We could have used an external real time clock to increase the precision
 but, on the one hand, this would have required a larger breadboard and,
 on the other hand, given the main goal of the system since - 
\series bold
\emph on
alarm 
\series default
clock
\emph default
 - an error of a few seconds a day does not affect its main function: triggering
 alarms
\emph on
 in the space of one minute
\emph default
; so we have preferred to synchronise the system with an external time source
 - Internet - in order to correct the drift.
\end_layout

